1 Abstract
As time passes, the presence of pollutants in waterways is increasing, with objects such as
microplastics or heavy metal particles posing an increasing level of health threat. Sensing of
waterborne particulates has accordingly become increasingly difficult as traditional methods
of filtration and sensing fall short. As such we have developed an algorithm capable of sensing,
locating, and volumetrically imaging suspended microparticles using a Gabor Inline
holography setup. The algorithm has demonstrated the ability to successfully volumetrically
image multiple particles as small as 200m with time scalability that would allow for use on
large scale. This algorithm opens the way to the implementation of large scale holographic
particulate sensors, whereby they provide the ability to visualize the exact nature of particles.

2 Introduction
This project aims to optimize the process of Gabor Inline holography, to enable detection, and
analysis, of microparticles flowing in a pipe. To do so means enabling real-time locating, and
3D reconstruction, of these particles from a recorded diffraction pattern. Current methods for
these can be slow and require optimization. This report sets out to outline an approach that
would allow real-time holographic imaging by optimizing or developing an algorithm that can
more efficiently reconstruct an object and then represent it volumetrically.

3 Literature Review
3.1 Light Basics
Waves can broadly be shown to fall into one of two types, longitudinal and transverse waves,
as seen in Error! Reference source not found.. In a longitudinal wave, the direction of
displacement is in the same direction as the propagation. In transverse waves, however, the
direction of displacement is perpendicular to the direction of propagation [1]. Light falls into
the category of transverse waves.
A second important distinction to make when discussing light waves is the difference between
plane and spherical waves. A plane wave is a constant-frequency wave with wavefronts that
are parallel planes normal to the propagation direction. A spherical wave is one emitted by a
point source whereupon spherical wavefronts move out in all directions [2]
3.2 Wave Optics
In the field of wave optics, light is treated as a wave. This allows for effects such as interference
and diffraction to be quantified. The most basic equation to be used in the field of wave optics
is the wave equation. Equation 1 shows the equation when considering only 1 spatial
dimension.

3.3 Diffraction Theory
Diffraction refers to the result of a wave encountering an obstacle or aperture. To satisfy the
conditions for diffraction, the size of the obstacle or aperture must be a similar size to the
wavelength of the incident light, specifically in the same magnitude. An aperture much larger
than the wavelength of the light will result in no diffraction happening, and an aperture with an
opening much smaller than the incident light will result in the formation of a point source. In
this case, as seen in Error! Reference source not found., the waves will bend around the
edges, resulting in the diffracting object or aperture becoming effectively a second source of a
wave [4].
Figure 3 Plane wave becoming spherical due to diffraction
The University of Auckland
8
When a plane wave is incident on such an object, it is of interest to find the field distribution
at a distance from the opening. To approach the problem a solution to the scalar wave equation
must be found with some constant initial conditions.

3.3.2 Fresnel Diffraction
Fresnel Diffraction refers to the situation where the source of the wave and the object are
located at a finite distance from the observation point. What this means is that incident wave
cannot be regarded as plane but must instead be analyzed as a spherical wave[5].
3.3.3 Fraunhofer Diffraction
A Fraunhofer diffraction is the situation where the source and object are located at a far distance
from the screen. As the distance between the object and the screen becomes large enough, the
wave front at the screen can be considered a plane wave[6]. Often known as the Far Field
Approximation, this is the approximation that can be applied to our experimental setup.
3.4 Holography Basics
Holography is the study of holograms, where a hologram is photograph of an interference
pattern, which contains the information regarding the 3D state of the scene. While photography
works by capturing the intensity of incident light on a sensor or film, holography also records
The University of Auckland
9
the phase, or complex component, of the wave. This means that when viewing a traditional
photograph, you are only viewing the amplitude of the image, which means you can see the
shape of the object but without any depth. This means that when we look at a photograph, we
can only see the shape of the object but without any depth. With phase information included
you can reconstruct a virtual object that displays depth [5]. With the recorded phase
information, it is possible to reconstruct the wavefront at various locations back from the
source, the process known as back propagation, these reconstructed slices of the wave front are
what allow the creation of a volumetric representation.
3.4.1 Object and Reference waves
For an object to be visible, it must be illuminated. When an object is illuminated, the light
waves that are reflected into our eyes, or a photographic plate, are called the object wave. The
object wave is characterized by both the amplitude and phase. Thus, two objects could have
the same amplitude but a different phase, indicating equal brightness but different shapes [7].
Photographs, however only record the amplitude of the object wave. To reconstruct a full object
wave, the properties of interference and diffraction of light must be used. The object wave is
allowed to interfere with a reference wave. This reference wave is created by the same light
source that created the object wave, but it travels directly to the photographic plate. Then, the
reference wave can interfere with the object wave since the reflection involved in creating the
object wave introduces a phase change relative to the reference wave. The resulting
interference pattern is often referred to as the interferogram.
Several different methods exist which allow for capture and subsequent recreation of a
complete object wave. Variations in the number of interferograms captured, as well as type and
direction of the reference beam, can be found [9].
3.4.2 Laser light
Laser light is used in holography due to its nature as a coherent wave. This means that its
frequency and waveform are identical, and the phase difference is constant [7]. A sustained
interference pattern is required. As such, variation in light waves, spatially or temporally,
would introduce variation that would make the pattern difficult to analyze [8]. However, it is
possible to do holography with a light that isnt a laser, such as rainbow holography, a type of
transmission holography whereby the hologram is illuminated from one side and viewed on
the other. Overall, the standard for holography is to use a coherent light source, however, as it
reduces the amount of analysis that needs to be done to complete the hologram[9].
3.4.3 Gabor Inline Holography
In Gabors original set up, a point source that would emit a spherical wave that would
illuminate the object, forming a highly magnified diffraction pattern on the recording screen
(see Figure 1) [8]. This recording is then transferred to a computer in which the reconstruction
can be completed numerically. Mathematically the goal is to recreate the wavefront at the
object by using a Kirchhoff-Helmholtz transform [9]. Upon reconstructing this wavefront at
The University of Auckland

several planes of differing distances from the recording screen, a 3D image can be constructed
from the 2D hologram.

3.5 Image Reconstruction
The role of reconstruction is to obtain the 3D structure of the object from the 2D image recorded
on the screen. This means reconstructing the wavefront at the object and can be achieved via a
Kirchhoff-Helmholtz transform. By reconstructing the wave front on a number of planes at
various distance from the source, at 3D image can be built up from the single 2D hologram.

Figure 4 Image of setup first created by Gabor [8]

3.5.1 Phase Shifting and Unwrapping
When using inline holography, it is necessary to remove what is known as the zeroth-order
light. The zeroth-order light is a phenomenon primarily caused by the diffractive properties of
the object and variances in wavelength; they combine to cause interference and noise, requiring
rectifying by what is known as phase shifting [10].
To use phase shifting the experimental set up includes a piezoelectric transducer mirror, which
allows phase shifting [11]. Multiple Interferograms are captured, with the phase of the
reference beam varied between each. A linear combination of these allows a single complex
valued hologram to be formed.
When using off-axis holography, phase unwrapping is needed. With only a single interference
pattern record the complex amplitude can be extracted. This is computationally expensive,
however as the process involves two 2D Fourier transforms and can take up to half a second
per megapixel of image [12].
3.5.2 Sectioning
Sectioning refers to the method by which a 3d shape is reconstructed by analyzing the outline
of multiple planes of the object by back-propagating the wavefront across the object.
When backpropagation has rendered the object sharply on the image plane, there are also
contributions from out-of-focus planes on either side of the sharp one. This means that it is
required to extract the information only regarding the in-focus plane to section it correctly.
3.5.3 Morphological Image Processing
Morphological techniques are used in image processing to make images simpler and easier to
analyze. Processes involved probe images with a small shape or template known as a
structuring element. This element is then placed in all possible locations and compared to the
neighbouring pixels; operations then can test how well the element fits the surrounding shape
of pixels[13].

4 Methods
4.1 Introduction
The experimental setup was a type of Gabor Inline holography. Using a laser as a light source,
it illuminated microspheres. This was recorded and then processed by Jo. Using various
methods, he was able to reconstruct the wavefront at numerous locations back from the source,
allowing for the creation of the data that was to be the input to my code. Although a complete
data set is extensive, 100+ slices at 4000x4000px resolution, it is possible to only focus on
slices and regions that contained particle outlines by cropping and excluding blank slices.
The first step in achieving volumetric representation of particles was the pre-processing and
Image Segmentation. The method employed was an iterative process. Several factors were
identified as being able to assist in these sectors and were then tested to see quantifiable
measures of their impact.
To identify a suitable method to volumetrically represent the objects, 3 methods were trialled.
These methods were the Trisurf function, the Volume Viewer app, and the Isosurface function.
Part of the process of ensuring the code was fit for its purpose meant testing its robustness.
Testing robustness in the case of this code was identified as the ability for the software to
handle edge cases, specifically different numbers of particles, particles of different sizes, and
particles of different shapes. Rather than adjust the experimental setup, it became easier to
create tester particles. As such, the objective was to make a function with the ability to create
edge case particles.
To examine the speed of the code, a method was devised to test the scaling of various sections
of the code. Rather than review it as one entire program, it was of interest to ensure the code
was modular. As such, the methodology to investigate the speed scaling revolved around
applying abstraction to the code, ensuring that as far as possible, sections of code were broken
down into separate functions, each performing only one task. Once this was achieved, it became
simple to implement several tests to verify the speed scaling of each small segment of code.
The choice was made to create the algorithm using MATLAB for several reasons. Firstly, due
to the nature of images, as matrices, MATLAB naturally is well suited with options for things
such as vectorization, to make working with matrices easier. Secondly, MATLAB has many
additional Toolboxes (libraries in any other language), that allow for expanded functionality
beyond what is built-in, and many of these are aimed at the sort of Image Processing problem
this project aims to tackle.

4.3 Pre-Processing and Image Segmentation
An integral part of any image processing problem is dealing with noise and cleaning up the
image. The Isosurface function works as a 3D analogue to an Isoline. It is a surface generated
by connecting points of equal value, whether pressure, temperature, etc.
As such, the inputs to the function are required to be well structured, closed shapes. In the
experimental data we collected, each particle suspended in the solution was a microsphere,
200m in diameter. With numerous 2D slices taken
through the sphere, the expectation was that each slice
would be a circle of sizes less than or equal to 200m.
This allowed us to have a baseline from which to gauge
how accurate the reconstructed holographic slices were.
As can be seen in Figure 7, the images with which we
were to create the 3D reconstruction were often far
from the shape the original particles were, and as such
a number of steps had to be taken to remove noise, clean
the image, and make it more faithful to the initially
imaged particle.

4.3.1 Threshold
When examining reconstructed slices for the presence of a particle, the method utilizes contrast.
The contrast threshold is slowly increased until there are no regions of high contrast left in the
image, quantified by a purely black image. After this, the contrast threshold is decreased by
some small amount, thus only revealing the particle that had the highest contrast, meaning it
was the particle that had the sharpest definition. This process was identified as being an area
where the quality of the input image could be strongly affected, and as such a method was
devised to investigate the effect of the threshold level on the quality of the outline of the shape.
4.3.2 Binarising Images
A straightforward way that was identified to allow for more consistent results was by binarising
the images. Artifacts can often be leftover from changing between file formats, compression,
etc. As such, it was deemed necessary to binarise all input images to reduce the likelihood of
errors caused by such abnormalities
4.3.3 Morphological Processes
One variable that allowed for better imaging of the particle is the size of the Structuring
Element. The structuring element is a shape or template that is positioned at every point on an
image and compared to the surrounding pixels. A match to the surrounding pixels can be
identified, allowing for further operations to be performed on the image. This means that it is
important for the structuring element to be a close match to the shape you wish to identify, as
it allows for more consistent and effective morphological operations to follow.
To test this, the same set of 10 slices of circles were closed, filled, and then displayed, each
time using a different sized structuring element so that the effect of the change in the structuring
element could be qualitatively examined.
4.4 Image Construction
Once image segmentation has occurred, the next step is to construct and display a volumetric
representation of the object. Numerous methods are available as volumetric construction tools,
and a number were considered to determine which option would provide the best fit to our
research goals.
4.4.1 Trisurf
The Trisurf function built into MATLAB was the first method that was tested for the ability to
successfully recreate the images in 3D. Trisurf works by plotting a 3D triangular surface
defined by vectors in the X, Y, and Z directions.
To approximate a sphere, initially, a rhombus was used for testing, as shown in Figure 8. This
test was sufficient to realize that this function would not be fit for purpose. The 3D
representation was severely limited by the fact that it was created by a Triangular Connectivity
Matrix, meaning the maximum resolution would be determined by the need for the function to
approximate any shape with triangles. Another issue that made this unsuitable was the intended
purpose; the Trisurf function is best suited for surface plots. Surface plots are intended to be
The University of Auckland
16
plots of a dependent variable, Z, against two independent variables, X and Y. As such, although
it did work to some degree for our purpose, it was discarded.
Figure 8 - Rhombus as produced by Trisurf

4.5 Creating Test Particles
Once the fundamentals of image segmentation and reconstruction were covered, it was of
interest to investigate the speed and robustness of the software. Due to this, it became viable to
create test particles that would allow for easy alteration to examine various edge cases rather
than requiring a change to the experimental setup. Accordingly, a program was created with
the ability to create a varying number of particles at varying sizes. The identified edge cases to
test for were very small and very large particles, multiple particles, and non-spherical particles.
The function created, CreateParticle, correspondingly had 4 settings. Between all different
settings, the number of slices was kept the same, as was the size of the image.
Examples of tests particles created can be seen in Section 5.4.
4.6 Speed Scaling
As stated in the research objectives, it is of interest for the program to be as fast as possible. As
such, a method was devised to test the way in which the speed of the code scaled with the size
of the image. There are two sections of the code expected to slow down the program, the image
filling step and the Image construction step.
4.6.1 Image Segmentation
The area of interest was specifically the code regarding the Imfill and Imclose functions. These
morphological processes are
This section of code was timed using the timeit function. This function runs multiple times and
averages it; however, the exact number of times it runs before averaging is not revealed in the
documentation. To test, an object comprising 10 slices was used, with image side length
ranging from 100px to 5000px, with a step size of 100px.
4.6.2 Image Construction
The Image Construction step was timed using the built-in time functions, tic and toc. The timeit
function was not suitable to measure the timing of this function as it requires a function call as
a parameter. The Tic and Toc function, however, can be called inline as they just record the
computer time at which they are used. As such, each sized image was tested 25 times and
averaged. Beyond this, the same method was followed to ensure comparability, with an object
comprising 10 slices, image sizes from 100-5000, and a step size of 100.
4.7 Locating in Space
As part of our research goal, it was also of interest to locate where the particle is located in 3D
space. To locate the particle in the Z direction is a simple matter, as the slices are taken at set
intervals, primarily 5m intervals.
The University of Auckland

To locate the particle in the X and Y directions, a different approach was needed. The camera

4.8 General Methodology
The first step in reproducing the volume was reading in the images; currently, by the limitations
of the RAM available, these slices are limited to being no more than 36 at a size of 4000x4000
px. This issue was worked around by Jotham cropping the images to only include the relevant
information, allowing this algorithm to process up to 100+ slices at a resolution of 400x400.
After reading in images, the next step was to perform morphological closing. This is done using
the Imclose function available as part of MATLABs Image Processing Toolbox. This step
allows for the closing of the image to a complete shape, in the case of most of the testing done
in this project, a circle. Upon successfully closing the image, the next step is filling in the shape,
again using a tool from the Image Processing toolbox, Imfill.
Following this, the image slices were smoothed and then were ready to be accepted by the
IsoSurface function.

5.1.3 Structuring Element
To successfully create a volume using Isosurface
requires that each slice consists of a closed shape
which is filled in. Closing and filling shapes are
operations that fall under the banner of morphological
image processing.
To close and fill each slice requires two commands,
Imclose and Imfill.
Imfill simply turns any non-white pixels contained
within white pixels to white.
However, given the nature of some of the holographic
reconstruction images, see fig 13, this isnt possible
until the shape has been closed sufficiently. The
Imclose function uses morphological closing,
involving the structuring element to close the image and smooth it. The structuring element is
a feature of the Imclose function that dictates the size of the disk to be used when smoothing
and closing the shape. As such, the larger the radius of the disk structuring element, the greater
the amount of smoothing. This only happens up to a certain point as beyond this the structuring
element has a size much larger than the shape it is attempting to close, and thus doesnt increase
the smoothing any further. To identify the best size structuring element as to give a circle.
Table 2 shows varying Structuring element sizes, from 1, where the shapes arent fully closed,
to 30. It appears that after 10/15 the effect of increasing the Structuring element size seems to
plateau, as such a value of 10 was chosen.

6 Discussion
During the course of the research project, several issues were raised concerning accurate
location of the particles, the speed of the algorithm, and the accuracy of the algorithm. These
issues are addressed below through a mixture of proposed solutions and further analysis.
6.1 Locating the particle
Although the process of locating particles inside each slice is trivial, as in Section 4.7, in the
context of the entire holographic reconstruction, it can be more troubling. As discussed in
Sections 4.1 and 4.7, the input data to the algorithm is cropped to only contain slices with
particles and only show the region containing the particle. Initially, it was considered that it
might be possible to simply work through a small subset of the slices sequentially; however, to
produce a completed volumetric image of every single particle in the volume requires that
every slice be input to the Isosurface function simultaneously.
As such, this problem has two potential solutions. The first solution is related to computer
hardware. MATLAB limits array stores memory allocation is constrained by the RAM of the
computer. With the 16Gb of RAM, the testing was run on MATLAB could store up to 30 slices
at a resolution of 4000x4000px. This means that although it could store the entirety of each
slice, it could only process a minimal number of slices. Accordingly, an increase in the amount
of RAM would be a simple way to locate the particle in space by allowing the entire volume
to be processed at once
The second solution would involve adding information to the data transfer to the Input data. If
when the images were cropped or specific slices were excluded, the information was included
in the folder of slices, it would be able to be incorporated into the location of the particle inside
each slice. Put simply, if the data were to include that it was a crop from X1Y1 to X2Y2, you
could simply add the value of X1 and Y1 to the location of the particle inside the cropped slice,
thus revealing the true location in the X and Y axes in the complete volume. This method
allows for the accurate location of the particles without the need for expanded computer
architecture, making it an attractive option.
6.2 Speed Scaling
The speed of the program is heavily influenced by the computer hardware used. The testing
done used 16Gb of RAM, a moderate amount for a home PC. However, it is likely if this
software was to be applied in a commercial setting that the amount of RAM available would
be significantly greater. Due to this large correlation between speed and available RAM, the
information regarding the speed should only be considered valid for the overall scaling trend,
not the absolute values of the time taken.
Options exist that could either improve the time taken or the absolute time taken. One method
to decrease the absolute time taken, besides increasing RAM, would be using parallelization.
Parallelisation utilizes multiple processors to complete tasks simultaneously. A way it could be
applied to our code would be by splitting the set of slices evenly into as many processors were
available and allowing these sets of slices to be worked on side by side. Another similar option
is the use of CUDA. CUDA works by instead utilizing GPUs, or Graphics Processing Units;
The University of Auckland
28
GPUs excel at doing simple mathematical calculations in lockstep, making them ideal for
handling large images or arrays.
One method that could potentially be used to decrease the time scaling would be the use of
vectorization. Vectorisation is a powerful tool available in MATLAB that allows for operations
to be applied as matrix operations rather than element by element. To apply vectorization to
our code would require further research as identifying areas that can be effectively vectorized
can often be difficult.
Overall, however, the speed scaling, linear with respect to the number of pixels, is a good result.
A general overview of algorithms indicates that in most cases, O(N) (where O represents the
worst-case run time of an algorithm with respect to the input size) is an excellent result and
beaten only by scalings such as O(logN) or O(1), the latter of which is nearly impossible to
achieve in practice for any algorithm of reasonable complexity.
6.3 Accuracy and Resolution
One problem encountered with the smoothing is that there exists the possibility for over
smoothing. With the data we have, knowing that the object being imaged is a perfect sphere,
we can be confident that the closer our object is to a sphere, the more accurate it is. As such,
we can confidently smooth the data to the maximum amount without being afraid of losing
details. However, it is possible that in some cases, such as when there is an overhang, or a small
protrusion on the particle being imaged, that this detail is lost.
The accuracy and resolution of the particles is a topic that needs to be approached in the context
of the wider problem being addressed. Within the scope of the project, the goal is to
volumetrically image and display suspended water particles. This means that the goal is not
necessarily to create a pixel-perfect reconstruction of the object, as that would provide no
additional benefit towards the objective. Rather, it is most important that the objects are
recognizable for what they are, microparticles, and that their overall size is accurately depicted.
This insight into the original research objectives provides an answer for the issue regarding
over-smoothing and the maximum resolution of the algorithm. It can be concluded that a large
smoothing ratio is best, as it allows for easy understanding of the particle being imaged, retains
the overall size, and doesnt include high-level details that are extraneous to the objective.
The University of Auckland
29
7 Summary and Conclusions
The results of this research project indicate the validity of the algorithm for use in the detection,
location, and volumetric representation of suspended microparticles.
Several methods were identified as being effective ways to pre-process the data. Adjusting the
threshold value allowed for clear slices to be used as input. Following this, the decision to
binarise the image allowed for an improvement in resolution and added robustness. The
morphological tools used, such as Imclose, and the Structuring Element, were powerful
functions allowing for the image segmentation to occur effectively.
The function Isosurface was proven to be an effective tool for the construction of a volumetric
representation when compared to alternatives such as the Volume viewer GUI or the Trisurf
function.
After investigation into the robustness and speed scaling of the algorithm, several conclusions
could be drawn. Firstly, the results of the speed scaling analysis indicate that although the
absolute time taken for different sections can be large, the scaling, or long-term trend, is
something to be highly satisfied with. An algorithm with component functions running at O(N)
means that it wont drastically increase in time taken as the size of the input is scaled up.
Beyond this, solutions are also proposed regarding computer architecture that could allow for
significant increases in the performance of the algorithm, both its speed and its ability to
accurately locate particles in the volume.
The robustness of the code was experimentally verified by testing numerous edge cases that
might be seen in a real-world setting, with all tests returning positive results.
This paper accordingly proposes Gabor Inline holography, in conjunction with the algorithm
that was created, as a viable method of sensing waterborne particulate matter. Proven methods
for pre-processing, image segmentation, and image construction are outlined, and their validity
confirmed. When considering the scaling up of the algorithm to a size fit for purpose, it is
shown that expanded computer hardware would provide great benefit but is not a requirement
as other alternatives exist.
